        "is_gated": false,
        "content": `
            <p>In 2019, Stanley was a brand most people had never thought about. A 110 year old company making vacuum insulated drinkware for outdoorsmen and construction workers, steady and functional and almost entirely invisible to the broader consumer market.</p>
            <p>By 2023, people were lining up outside Starbucks at 5am for a limited edition colourway. The Stanley Quencher had become a cultural object. A status symbol. A collectible.</p>
            <p>The product barely changed. Everything else did.</p>
            
            <h3>The Man Who Had Done It Before</h3>
            <p>Before Stanley, Terence Reilly was the Chief Marketing Officer of Crocs. Yes, those Crocs. The ones that spent a decade as the internet's favourite punchline, the foam clogs that became shorthand for not caring about how you looked.</p>
            <p>Reilly took Crocs from cultural joke to genuine cultural moment. Limited edition collaborations with Post Malone, Bad Bunny, and high fashion labels turned a product people were embarrassed to own into something people waited in line for. The irreverence became the identity. The ugliness became the appeal.</p>
            <p>When Reilly joined Stanley as global president in 2020, he brought the same instinct with him. Find the audience nobody has thought to talk to. Make them feel seen. Then make the product feel like it belongs to them. He asked one question that changed everything. What if women were the target audience?</p>
            
            <h3>The Numbers</h3>
            <p>Stanley's revenue went from 75 million dollars in 2022 to 750 million dollars in 2023. One year. Same product. Ten times the revenue.</p>
            <p>That number requires sitting with for a moment. The tumbler did not get a significant redesign. The manufacturing did not change. The core function, keeping your drink cold for an unreasonable amount of time, remained exactly as it had always been.</p>
            <p>What changed was the feeling around it. The colours, the community, the sense that this object belonged to a specific kind of person and that person was aspirational. Reilly has said that marketing is fundamentally about connection, and Stanley built connection so deliberately and so specifically that the product became almost secondary to what it represented.</p>
            
            <h3>The Car Fire</h3>
            <p>In 2023 a woman posted a Tik Tok of her car after it caught fire. Everything inside had been destroyed. Except one thing sitting in the cup holder, completely intact, ice reportedly still inside. Her Stanley tumbler. The video reached 95 million views.</p>
            <p>What Reilly did next is the part worth studying. He did not let the moment pass. He stitched the video, offered his sympathy, and announced that Stanley would replace her car and send her new tumblers. His response generated 6.7 million likes. The caption was: <em>Stanley's got your back.</em></p>
            <p>That is not a marketing campaign. That is a brand behaving like a human being in a moment that called for it. And in a media landscape saturated with corporate messaging and carefully worded statements, a brand simply showing up felt extraordinary. It worked because it was specific, immediate, and genuinely generous. Not a press release. Not a brand values statement. Just a real response to a real moment.</p>
            
            <h3>The Scarcity Engine</h3>
            <p>Stanley did not just make a good product and wait for people to find it. They made it feel rare.</p>
            <p>Limited edition colourways released with almost no warning. Influencer collaborations that sold out within hours. A Starbucks partnership that turned a Tuesday morning into a queuing event. The cup became a collectible and collectibles require exclusivity to maintain their cultural value.</p>
            <p>This is the psychology behind every successful luxury brand applied to a product at an accessible price point. A Stanley tumbler costs around fifty dollars. The feeling it was engineered to deliver, the sense of being in on something, of owning a version that not everyone could get, that feeling is worth considerably more than fifty dollars to the people who want it. Aspirational but accessible. That is the sweet spot that an entire generation responds to.</p>
            
            <h3>What Stanley Actually Sold</h3>
            <p>The tumbler did not change much between 2019 and 2023. The product in the hands of the woman in the car fire is not dramatically different from the one sitting forgotten in an outdoorsman's garage years earlier. What changed was the story around it. The community that formed around specific colourways. The Zoom backgrounds and desk aesthetics and Tik Tok hauls. The sense that owning one meant something about the kind of person you were.</p>
            <p>Stanley did not go viral. Stanley made people feel seen. And that is a completely different thing.</p>
            <p>Women were not buying a water bottle. They were buying into an identity, a community, an aesthetic that showed up in their daily lives and told a story about them that they wanted to tell. Reilly understood something that a lot of brands still do not. The product is never really the product. The feeling is the product. Get the feeling right and the product sells itself.</p>
            
            <h3>The Lesson</h3>
            <p>The Stanley story is not really about tumblers. It is about what happens when someone looks at an existing product and asks who has been ignored. A 110 year old brand had been talking to one audience for its entire existence. Reilly looked at it and saw a different audience entirely, one that had not been spoken to, one that would respond to being seen, one that would build a community around a product if the product gave them something to gather around.</p>
            <p>He changed the colours. He changed the target. He responded to a car fire like a human being. And he turned 75 million dollars into 750 million in twelve months. Same product. Completely different feeling.</p>
        `
